he practice of translation in equal but not opposite measure. Poetry has a transforming yet ever-acute relevance in Chinese culture, and this makes it a good entry point for studying Chinese-foreign encounters. Pushing past oppositions that still too often restrict discussions of translation-form versus content, elegance versus accuracy, and "the original" versus "the translated" - this volume brings a wealth of new thinking to the interrelationships between poetry, translation, and China.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aLiterature (General). 4aAsian Studies. 4aEast Asia and North East Asia. 4aLanguage Studies. 4aLiterary Theory, Criticism, and History. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Writing / Poetry.2bisacsh  aTranslation, poetry, China.1 aAdmussen, Nick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAllen, Joseph R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColeman, Tara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrevel, Maghiel van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrevel, Maghiel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEdmond, Jacob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodman, Eleanor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIdema, Wilt L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlein, Lucas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlein, Lucas, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKrenz, Joanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 